Scotland’s private schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another crop of outstanding exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest standard to pupils and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it hits him in the head.
But if you speak to him in his own language, it will reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year’s recent exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the table and with the highest pass rates in private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved an outstanding mark.
The data, compiled from the 74 schools that make up SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained honors enrollment in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, languages are being given the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private school programs and of all kinds.
A survey by the UK’s Employment and Training Commission in 2014 found that a lack of language skills accounted for 17 per cent of the reasons why employers struggle to fill vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as there are more job opportunities that require languages.
Regardless of the chosen career, if they learn a second language they will have a real advantage in the future with a life-long skill like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will place a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, in this case 15%.
That’s why it’s so important to invest in a language for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, the languages of instruction differ according to the school.
Some schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others opt for languages considered more important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what the interests of your children are, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialist teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialise in providing a learning environment that equips children and staff with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
We cannot deny that at this moment, in a global business environment, that languages remain of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
It has to be done.
