"However, we do not see the corresponding response from the US," he added.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and in such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disarmament on our part first.”
While Ri echoed well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to "gradual" denuclearisation under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action, his statement seemed important, as he did not reject unilateral denuclearisation as had happened with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to "denuclearize" the Korean Peninsula "as long as Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has long sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has declared that Pyongyang must first lay down its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal of coercive force, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can make us kneel is an impossible dream for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions exacerbate our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added, "If the other side of this denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to a standstill."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the United Nations General Assembly it was inevitable to strike the United States with North Korean missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket man on a suicide mission.”
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking steps toward disarmament, but said much work remains to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea is denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for that, and that "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three or five months."
China and Russia are discussing whether the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
