Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
This year, a new course from Harvard University is getting all its students to sleep longer in order to combat the growth of the sexist culture of studying all night long stimulated by caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world’s number one university are often unaware of the basics about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact that lack of sleep had on learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you only telling me this now, in my senior year?’
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basics about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improves overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficit affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this information, just as we have a right to know what the health effects are if we choose to smoke tobacco,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in staying up all night still exists, he says, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students that involved lack of sleep was a growing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep and good quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" for combating stress, fatigue and anxiety, he says. Even avoiding getting fat, since lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes it constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for bedtime, as well as for when they wake up. Likewise, it is recommended that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can unbalance the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
