However, he was killed by a sniper four days later without knowing that he had been awarded the highest British military decoration.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren were tasked with discovering a memorial in his honour at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
Michael Vann, one of his grandchildren, highlighted the symbolism of discovering this monument just 100 years after his grandfather’s feat that earned him the title.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog and under the yoke of intense machine-gun fire".
He then rushed to the line of fire and, with "great courage", directed the line forward before rushing in with a cannon and without any help from anyone, and shooting down three people from the enemy detachment.
Lt. Col. Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "something I could never live with, but a lesson nonetheless".
He and his brother Dr. James Vann also placed a wreath after the parade, which headlined the Brentwood Imperial youth band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to participate in the parade" and added that "the value of this genuine hero is demonstrated by the support of so many people."
