Germany's new warship postponed once again
The German Navy’s newest frigate should have been delivered in 2014 to replace aging Cold War-era warships, but it won’t arrive until at least next year due to faulty systems and rising cost, local media reported.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the leading ship of the new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates, was postponed until the first half of 2019, a military spokesman told the newspaper Die Zeit.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but post-delivery problems affected the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-W<0xC3><0xBC>rttemberg-class ships, which the Navy commissioned in 2007, will replace the former Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, with different anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as with concealment technology, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, it should be possible to deploy the younger frigates up to two years outside the ports of origin.
However, as Die Zeit points out, these continuous delays mean that warships with the latest technology, and which will allow Germany to project its power abroad, will be outdated when they enter service.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy returned a ship to a builder after delivery.
Little was known about the motives behind this return, but the German media reported "crucial flaws in the software and hardware" that made it impossible to use the warship in a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors; that is, half of the personnel needed on the former Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, the ship was found to have a dramatic excess weight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add improvements in the future.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is thought to weigh twice as much as the similar-class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the total price of the project, which includes crew training, is also becoming an issue.
It is claimed that it has already reached the astonishing amount of 3.1 billion euros, compared to the initial 2.2 billion.
The problems of the newer frigates take on special importance in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval power is waning.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defense committee of the German parliament, acknowledged that the Navy is running out of ships suitable for deployment.
The officer states that this problem is growing, as older ships have been retired, but not replaced by others.
He also regretted that none of the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
National Trust Spies on the Secret Life of Bats
New research being carried out on a Scottish Highlands estate aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to forage for food.
The results are expected to shed light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bats Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in the gardens of Inverewe at Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with hand-held detectors.
A sound analysis performed by experts from all the recordings will determine the frequency of the calls of the bats and what each species is doing.
Next, a habitat map will be developed to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and how best to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works affecting nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do fly glue traps, some chemical treatments of building materials, and domestic cat attacks.
The bats are not blind.
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when hunting.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who carry out periodic surveys, inspections of children and, sometimes, even rescues.
The organisation even has Scotland's only and first reserve of bats at the Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, manager of Estate, says this is the ideal territory for them.
"At Threate we have a great area for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, historic trees and a great habitat.
But there’s a lot we still don’t know about bats, so the work we’ve done here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
It highlights the importance of controlling the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance tasks on the properties, since it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest can kill up to 400 females and offspring, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"There's still a lot to learn about bats, and for many of the species, we don't know how their populations are doing."
