Red tide information: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to the most recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission, there is a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the commission, increasingly uneven upwelling conditions are being observed in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties areas, which may mean that concentrations are decreasing.
The red tide extends approximately 210 km from the coast from the northern counties of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Concentrations of 10 miles (16 km) can be found off the coast of Hillsboroug County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
The red tide was also found in Pasco County.
Mid-level concentrations were reported on the coast or off the coast of Pinellas County last week, bottom and high concentrations were reported off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom and high concentrations were reported on or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom and low-level concentrations were reported on Charlotte County, bottom and high concentrations were reported on or off the coast of Hillsborough County, and bottom and high concentrations were reported on or off the coast of Collier County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties, reports of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No such cases have been reported in Northwestern Florida in the past week.
